Health Care Cost Prediction

Srujana Dandem

November 20, 2023

Introduction

Kaggle Dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/teertha/ushealthinsurancedataset/data

Health insurance companies use a complex formula in order to assess how much they should charge people for health insurance. They do so by taking into account various factors like age, weight, past ailments, etc. My aim is to create a predictive model for determining which factors most influence health insurance costs and how much a person would be charged based on these factors. In order to do so, I will be looking at health insurance data that I found on Kaggle. The website link is attached above. Thus, my hypothesis is as follows:

Hypothesis: The attributes age, BMI, and number of children under the insurance plan are significant factors of influence in determining health care insurance charges.

I have chosen these particular attributes since based off of my own background knowledge on the domain, I believe they hold the greatest influence in how much a person is charged by healthcare insurance companies. I picked age since with old age, one would likely have greater ailments and hence health costs. I picked children since with the additional number of dependents being covered by the insurance policy, the insurance charge is also likely to be raised. Finally, I picked BMI since it is an overall indicator of the health of any person, and so would be relevant as well.

Correlation Heat Map

(Source:https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/how-to-create-correlation-heatmap-in-r/)

We shall now make a correlation heat map for all of our variables. In order to do so, we must first convert our categorical variables to be encoded as numeric. We do so by using the as.numeric() function.

# Converting categorical variables to numeric
insurance$sex <- as.numeric(factor(insurance$sex))
insurance$region <- as.numeric(factor(insurance$region))
insurance$smoker <- as.numeric(factor(insurance$smoker))

# Selecting variables
variables <- c("age", "sex", "bmi", "region", "smoker", "children", "charges")

# creating the correlation matrix
corr_mat <- round(cor(insurance[variables]), 2)

# reduce the size of correlation matrix
melted_corr_mat <- melt(corr_mat)

# plotting the correlation heatmap
ggplot(data = melted_corr_mat, aes(x = Var1, y = Var2, fill = value)) + 
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  geom_text(aes(label = value), color = "black", size = 4) +
  labs(title = "Correlation Heatmap",
       x = "", y = "") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colors = c("#a6bddb", "#2b8cbe", "#045a8d"))

Through this correlation heatmap, we are able to see just how much of a correlation there lies between each of the variables. When independent variables are highly correlated, change in one variable would cause change to another and so the model results fluctuate significantly. We thus would want to avoid this for an accurate model. We observe that there isnt much correlation at all between the explanatory variables. This is a good sign since it indicates that there is a low multicollinearity in our data, which is ideal. We also observe that the correlation for the response variable charges has the highest correlation with the explanatory variable smoker, at 0.79 correlation. This indicates that smoker might be a crucial factor of influence on charges. This is followed by age at 0.3 correlation, and bmi at 0.2 correlation. However, the correlation levels of age and bmi are significantly lower when compared to smoker.

After our trials, we find that mod5 has the best fit out of the above models. This is because it has the highest Adjusted R^2 values at 0.633.

\(R^2\) is the proportion of the total variation in the response variable that is accounted for by the model. The value of R^2 lies between zero and one. When R^2 = 0, the model accounts for none of the variance of the response values: the model is useless. When R = 1, the model captures all of the variance of the response values: the model values are exactly on target.

Over here, having an R^2 value of 0.633 indicates that 63.3% of the variance in our response value is being accounted for by our model. This is a considerably good fit, but still not the best.

The second highest adjusted R^2 occurs with mod1 at 0.088, which is considerably lesser. Though, mod5 has a relatively larger Standard Error and thus larger confidence interval when compared to the rest of the models, upon taking into consideration the massive difference in Adjusted R^2, we shall choose mod5 as the best model. Moreover, smoker is also a statistically significant variable, given how its p-value < 0.05.

Thus, we shall continue with our experimentation for model building, holding the first explanatory term fixed as smoker.

We include modC since it a representation of our Hypothesis claim, which says that age, BMI and children are significant factors in determining health care insurance costs. However, as we can see from the summary, modCs Adjusted R^2 is extremely low compared to that of modA and modB. modC explains only about 12% of the variation in the data. Hence, we can safely conclude that modC fits our data poorly, and so we discard modC from our consideration. Thus, we also fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Predicting on Training Set

Now that we have our finalized our initial models, modA and modB, we shall evaluate the performance of the models by making predictions on the training set.

# Testing modA on Training Set
pred_trainingA <- predict(modA, training)

# Calculating residuals
residuals_trainingA <- training$charges - pred_trainingA

# Calculating RMSE
rmse_trainingA <- sqrt(mean(residuals_trainingA^2))

rmse_trainingA
## [1] 6059.26
# Testing modB on Training Set
pred_trainingB <- predict(modB, training)

# Calculating residuals

# Calculating RMSE

Models Validation

Let us now evaluate the performance of our selected initial models, on the validation set.

# Testing modA on Validation Set
pred_validationA <- predict(modA, validation)

residuals_validationA <- validation$charges - pred_validationA

# Calculating RMSE
rmse_validationA <- sqrt(mean(residuals_validationA^2))

pred_validationB <- predict(modB, validation)

A lower RMSE value indicates that the model fits the data better. Hence, we will be choosing modA as our final model.

Model Testing

We can now test the performance of our finalized model on the Test set.

# Testing Model on Test Set
pred_testA <- predict(modA, test)

# Calculating residuals
residuals_testA <- test$charges - pred_testA

# Calculating RMSE
rmse_testA <- sqrt(mean(residuals_testA^2))

rmse_testA
## [1] 6454.515

Results

Given that a lower RMSE value determines a better fitting model, we find that our final chosen model: charges ~ smoker + age + bmi had varying performance results on the training, validation and test sets. We found an RMSE of 6059.26 on the training set, 5871.63 on the validation set, and 6454.52 on the test set. This indicates that the model performed best on the validation set and worst on the training set.

Residual Plot

The residuals can be derived as follows: Residual = Observed Values - Predicted Values

# Calculating residuals
residuals_testA <- test$charges - pred_testA

# Making a data frame with the predicted values and residuals for modA on the test set
residuals_df <- data.frame(Predicted = pred_testA, Residual = residuals_testA)

# Making the residuals scatterplot for modA
ggplot(data = residuals_df, aes(x = Predicted, y = Residual)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue", shape = 16) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Residual Plot", x = "Predicted Values", y = "Residuals")

We observe that the residuals dont seem to follow any particular pattern and are randomly scattered around the horizontal axis. This is a good indication as it implies that our model is a good fit.

Conclusion and Improvements

Overall, in the end we fail to reject the null hypothesis that Age, BMI and Children are not significant factors of influence in determining insurance charges. However, two of the variables we had initially hypothesized to be significant factors, did in fact prove to be significant as showcased by the age and bmi terms in our final model: charges ~ smoker + age + bmi . Hence overall, our final result is that the attributes smoker, age, and bmi have significant influence on determining health care insurance costs.

Given more time though, I would definitely wish to build more variations of the models and compare their R^2 values, confidence intervals, and p-values. I would also start doing the ANOVA tests earlier on in order to have a more thorough analysis in my initial model selections as well. There are many more permutations that are possible with the variables in our data. Each model adds to our understanding of what might produce the best fit. Given the scope and time of this project though, it wasnt possible to go through all of them. Should I have the time and resources however, I would also wish to gain further background and knowledge around the topic of health insurance costs. Ultimately, a the model needs to be built using our best judgement, and in order to enable that, deep domain knowledge is key for that intrinsic intuition around the subject and to make the most fruitful hypotheses. Finally, in order to gain the most positive benefit from the model, I would seek to test if controlling for factors like smoking or bmi would allow people to decrease their healthcare insurance charges.

Appendix B - Data Dictionary

  • age: age of primary beneficiary; units: years
  • sex: insurance contractor gender (female/male)
  • bmi: body mass index, providing an understanding of body, weights that are relatively high or low relative to height, objective index of body weight (kg / m ^ 2) using the ratio of height to weight, ideally 18.5 to 24.9
  • children: number of children covered by health insurance / Number of dependents; units: children
  • smoker: smoking (yes/no)
  • region: the beneficiarys residential area in the US (northeast/southeast/southwest/northwest)
  • charges: individual medical costs billed by health insurance; units: USD
